body:
CARD FOR DENISE/ PART THREE/ WEATHER SUPERSTITIONS

'Red Sky at night, shepherd's delight': 
-A sign of wet weather to come 
-It's because dry particles in the air cause this slight redness in the sky. 


'Rainbow in the morning: Take this as a warning'
-There's stormy weather to come 
-It's because a rainbow in the west indicates moisture in the air as most storms come from west to east 


'If cows are lying down it means it's going to rain' 
-One theory is that cows are able to sense the approaching rain, either through increased moisture in the air or the accompanying drop in air pressure.
title: CARD: WEATHER SUPERSTITIONS

body:
CARD FOR CHARLENE / PART THREE / CAN YOU CATCH A CHILL FROM BEING COLD, THE FACTS

- According to one GP the cold can't actually give you a cold

- When it's cold, people tend to cluster together indoors, so there's an association between the winter months and an increased risk of viral illness

- Another GP says cold weather may reduce the effectiveness of our first line of defence - which are the nostrils. When the tiny hairs in our nostrils waft, they prevent viruses getting into the system. Cold weather makes these wafting movements less efficient.

- Another source suggests that we catch colds more easily due to our lack of vitamin D in the winter. We get vitamin D from the sun and it's said to play an essential role in strengthening immune system.
title: CARD: CAN YOU CATCH A CHILL FROM BEING COLD
